Product Version     25.10    Cadence Design Systems, Inc.
setLibraryUnit(25.10)                                    setLibraryUnit(25.10)

Name
       setLibraryUnit  -  Sets  the  time and capacitance unit values for con-
       straints and report generation

Syntax
       setLibraryUnit

       [-help]

       [-cap <capUnit>]

       [-time <timeUnit>]

       Sets the time and capacitance unit values for  constraints  and  report
       generation.

       The  timing  constraints (SDC) files do not contain any unit specifica-
       tion for capacitance and time values. Hence, the units for these values
       are considered to be same as those specified in the  timing  libraries.
       The commands, e.g., report_timing, require consistent units to generate
       reports.  If  an  inconsistency occurs in the timing libraries, the de-
       fault unit of time (as ns) and capacitance (as pf) is used.

       You can use this command when you need to override the  library  units,
       or force the setting of units when libraries have different units.

       Note:  You  must  set  the setLibraryUnit command before the design and
       constraints are read.

Parameters
       -help  Prints a brief description that includes the  type  and  default
              information for each setLibraryUnit parameter.

              For a detailed description of the command and all of its parame-
              ters, use the man command:

              man setLibraryUnit.

       -cap <capUnit>
              Specifies the capacitance load unit in the timing library.

              Default: 1.0 pf

       -time <timeUnit>
              Specifies  the  time unit to be used for timing constraints. The
              valid values are 1ns, 1ps, 10ps, 100ps.

              Default: 1.0 ns

Example
              * The following command sets the time unit  for  the  design  to
                10ps:

                setLibraryUnit -time 10ps

Related Information
              * Timing Analysis chapter in the Innovus User Guide

